Prediction of Benign and Malignant Breast Cancer

Harika Panuganty

4/3/2021

Introduction This dataset is publicly available on Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data) and looks at the physical features of a breast mass from digitized images from a file needle aspirate biopsy.

Breast cancer is the second leading cause of cancer death in women, with over 250,000 affected in 2018. Misdiagnoses of benign and malignant tumors can be detrimental towards treatment efforts as treatment options differ greatly between the two. This dataset consists of biopsies from breast cancer patients in Wisconsin and the database is UCI’s Machine Learning Repository.

The goal of this project is to determine whether a breast mass tumor is malignant or benign based on several different physical factors.

Classes and Variables This dataset consists of 3 classes: - means, standard error (SE) and worst (i.e., mean of three largest values in each variable) and 32 variables: 1. Radius: Distance from center to points on perimeter 2. Texture: Standard deviation of gray-scale values 3. Perimeter: Size of core tumor 4. Area: Area of tumor 5. Smoothness: Local variation in radius lengths 6. Compactness: [(Mean of perimeter)^2/area] - 1.0 7. Concavity: Depth of concave portions of contours in tumor 8. Concave.points: No. of concave portions of the contour 9. Symmetry: Tumor symmetry 10. Fractal Dimension: Pattern changes depending on scale measured in

Project Methodology: In addition to predicting the classification of breast tumor, we wanted to find the most effective variable in determining malignancy or benignity of the tumor. This is how we did it: - Utilized two predictive modelling techniques: logistic regression (baseline) and neural networks We settled on 4 logistic regression models and 4 neural networks testing the different classes: All variables, Mean Variables, Worst variables + SE variables

Our model parameters were: Logistic Regression Train-test split: 70:30 Neural Networks Number = 3; 3 resampling iterations Grid size 2-50 with 1 layer in between Decay rate = 5e-4

bcdata <- read.csv("~/Desktop/data.csv", header = TRUE)

#data cleaning
bc_data <- within(bcdata, rm(X)) #removed random X column in dataset
#summary(bc_data)

#as.factor diagnosis to determine if its a binary variable
bc_data$diagnosis <- as.factor(bc_data$diagnosis)

#we need as.factor to create as.integer
bc_data$diagnosis <- as.integer(bc_data$diagnosis == "M")

#as.factor to change the binary variable
bc_data$diagnosis <- as.factor(bc_data$diagnosis)
#summary(bc_data)

set.seed(345)
#to create a 70-30 split
bc_data_split <- createDataPartition(bc_data$diagnosis, p=.7, list = FALSE, times=1)

head(bc_data_split) #to double check
##      Resample1
## [1,]         2
## [2,]         3
## [3,]         4
## [4,]         6
## [5,]         7
## [6,]         9
#Split data into test and train
bc_data.train <- bc_data[bc_data_split,]
bc_data.test <- bc_data[-bc_data_split,]

#Logistic regression on train dataset against all variables
bc_data.train.log <- glm(diagnosis~., data=bc_data.train, family="binomial")
## Warning: glm.fit: algorithm did not converge
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
#Perform prediction on test dataset
bc_data.test$pred_diagnosis <- predict.glm(bc_data.train.log, newdata = bc_data.test, type="response")

#First create a prediction object
pred <- roc(response = bc_data.test$diagnosis, predictor = bc_data.test$pred_diagnosis, direction = "<")

#Get AUC performance = 0.936953 
auc_perf <- auc(pred)
cat("AUC: ", auc_perf, "\n")
## AUC:  0.9430352
#AUC 95% CI = 0.8977693 0.936953 0.9761367 
ci_auc_perf <- ci.auc(pred)
cat("95% CI: ", ci_auc_perf, "\n")
## 95% CI:  0.9056792 0.9430352 0.9803911

Below chunk of code consists of: Creating forestplot for logistic regression The AUC’s and 95% CI for each of the classes are very narrow and it is difficult to identify the best AUC value and the tightest 95% CI, so below is a forest plot to clearly show and compare between the classes. Taking a look at this plot, we can note that class All mean + SE has the best AUC and a tight 95% CI therefore being the best logistic regression model out of the 4.

library(ggplot2)

Below chunk of code consists of: Neural Network for ALL variables

library(nnet)

# Changing the response into a format recognized by caret
bc_data.train$diagnosis_cat <- ifelse(bc_data.train$diagnosis == 1, "Yes", "No") 

bc_data.test$diagnosis_cat <- ifelse(bc_data.test$diagnosis == 1, "Yes", "No") 

#Set training parameters
fit_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 3, classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
#trainControl= control the computational nuances of the train function
#Method- resampling method "cv"- for repeated training/test splits
#number- either the number of folds or number of resampling iterations
#classProbs- a logical; should class probabilities be computed for classification models in each resample?
#summaryFunction- function to compute performance metrics across resamples. twoClassSummary- metric that relies on class probabilities

#set a grid of parameters to train over
nnet_params <- expand.grid(size = seq(from = 2, to = 50, by = 1), decay = 5e-4)
#expand.grid- create a data fram from all combinations of supplied vectors, size = seq is the size of the grid

#Create model on training data 
bc_data.model <- train(diagnosis_cat ~ radius_mean+texture_mean+perimeter_mean+area_mean+smoothness_mean+compactness_mean+ concavity_mean+concave.points_mean+symmetry_mean+fractal_dimension_mean+radius_se+texture_se+perimeter_se+area_se+smoothness_se+compactness_se+ concavity_se+concave.points_se+symmetry_se+fractal_dimension_se+radius_worst+texture_worst+perimeter_worst+area_worst+smoothness_worst+compactness_worst+concavity_worst+concave.points_worst+symmetry_worst+fractal_dimension_worst, data = bc_data.train, method = "nnet", metric = "ROC", trControl = fit_control, tuneGrid = nnet_params, trace = FALSE)

Below chunk of code consists of: Creating forestplot for Neural Networks The AUC’s and 95% CI for each of the classes are very narrow and it is difficult to identify the best AUC value and the tightest 95% CI, so below is a forest plot to clearly show and compare between the classes. Taking a look at this plot, we can note that class All has the best AUC and a tight 95% CI therefore being the best neural network model out of the 4.

library(ggplot2)
forest.plot.nn <- read.csv("~/Desktop/forestplot.nn.csv", header = TRUE)

Below chunk of code consists of: Variable Importance Plot for ALL Neural Networks (the best model) Comparing the values and the plots, we’ve confirmed that the best model (between logistic regression and neural networks) is All neural networks. Going one step further, we wanted to see which variable within this All neural network model would best determine the benign/malignant outcome of the tumor. To determine this, we created a variable importance plot as shown below.

As we observe, area_se, radius_worst and perimeter_mean are the most effective variables, greatest to least, respectively.

library(randomForest)
library(ggplot2)
library(nnet)

this_mtry = floor(sqrt(ncol(bc_data.train)))

set.seed(345)
m.RF <- train(diagnosis_cat ~ radius_mean+texture_mean+perimeter_mean+area_mean+smoothness_mean+compactness_mean+ concavity_mean+concave.points_mean+symmetry_mean+fractal_dimension_mean+radius_se+texture_se+perimeter_se+area_se+smoothness_se+compactness_se+ concavity_se+concave.points_se+symmetry_se+fractal_dimension_se+radius_worst+texture_worst+perimeter_worst+area_worst+smoothness_worst+compactness_worst+concavity_worst+concave.points_worst+symmetry_worst+fractal_dimension_worst, data=bc_data.train,
         method = "rf",
         metric= "ROC",
         tunegrid = grid_params,
         ntree = 10,
         trControl = train_control_params)

variable.imp <- varImp(bc_data.model)

Below chunk of code consists of: Combining ForestPlot for both Logistic Regression and Neural Networks The forestplot here shows both individual forest plots and we can clearly see the All Neural Network has the highest AUC and the tightest 95%CI out of all the logistic regression and neural network models, therefore being the best at predicting malignancy/benignity of breast cancer tumors.
